    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically someone else just keeps the money in a middle spot so no one gets ripped off? who usually handles that, like a bank or a lawyer? and does the money just sit there doing nothing until the end?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, exactly! The escrow account is managed by a neutral third party, often a bank or an escrow company, which holds the funds until the conditions of the sale are met. The money is not just sitting there idle; it's actively safeguarding your money, ensuring that it's used only for its intended purpose—closing the deal on your new home. The escrow agent will release the funds to the seller once all conditions are fulfilled, and then they will be transferred to you once you've completed your obligations, like paying off your mortgage and transferring the title. This whole process helps to prevent any misunderstandings or disputes between buyer and seller, making the transaction smoother and more secure.",
